# 🌌 VIIRS Nighttime Lights Mapping for Ghana: Implementation Guide

This guide details the complete technical workflow, data requirements, and code needed to produce a high-contrast, premium "nightlights" map of Ghana similar to NASA's global visualizations. It covers data acquisition, preprocessing (specifically tackling raw skewness), and cartographic styling in R.

```
       GHANA NIGHTLIGHTS CONCEPTUAL VISUALIZATION
       
                 ^  [Upper West]   [Upper East]
                / \      *              *
               |   |        [Northern]
               |   |            * (Tamale)
               |   |
               |   |        [Ashanti]
               |   |       * (Kumasi)
               \   /
                \ /        * (Accra)  [Greater Accra]
                 v  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
                    Gulf of Guinea (Dark Ocean Backdrop)
```

---

## 🛠️ Prerequisites & Package Setup

To run this pipeline, you will need standard R spatial libraries. Install them in your R console before running the script:

```R
# Install required libraries from CRAN
install.packages(c("tidyverse", "sf", "terra", "tidyterra", "geodata"))
```

### Key Libraries Explained
*   **`sf`**: Handles vector data (administrative borders).
*   **`terra`**: Handles large, high-performance raster operations (clipping, masking, transformations).
*   **`tidyterra`**: Provides `geom_spatraster()` to directly map raster objects inside `ggplot2`.
*   **`geodata`**: Automates downloading administrative boundaries from GADM.

---

## 📡 Data Acquisition Options

To map Ghana, you need two datasets:
1.  **Administrative Boundaries (Vector)**: Easily fetched programmatically via `geodata::gadm()`.
2.  **VIIRS Nighttime Lights (Raster)**: There are three main ways to acquire this.

### Option 1: Google Earth Engine (Recommended for No-Setup Preview)
If you already use Earth Engine, the `rgee` package in R or Python's `ee` library is the fastest way to get cloud-free annual composites (e.g., the `NOAA/VIIRS/DNB/MONTHLY_V1/VCMSLCFG` or newer V2 annual collections) without downloading large files.

### Option 2: NASA Black Marble & the `blackmarbler` R Package
The World Bank's `blackmarbler` package downloads NASA's officially corrected Black Marble products (`VNP46A1`/`VNP46A2` for daily, `VNP46A3` for monthly, `VNP46A4` for annual).
*   **Note**: Requires a free NASA Earthdata account. You must pass your account's **bearer token** as an argument in the function `bm_raster()`.

### Option 3: Manual GeoTIFF Download (EOG / World Bank)
Download the pre-processed regional annual composite directly as a GeoTIFF:
*   **Source**: Colorado School of Mines Earth Observation Group (EOG): [EOG VNL Products](https://eogdata.mines.edu/products/vnl/)
*   **World Bank "Light Every Night"**: Host Cloud-Optimized GeoTIFFs (COGs) of nightlights.

---

## 🎨 Visual Design System for "Glow" Aesthetics

To match the premium look of NASA's visualizations, we must design the map with care:

### 1. The Logarithmic Transformation (Critical)
Nightlight intensity values are heavily skewed. The difference between Accra's bright center and a small rural village is orders of magnitude. 
*   **Without log-scaling**: Accra/Kumasi will appear as tiny white dots, and 95% of Ghana will appear pitch black.
*   **With log-scaling (`log1p(x)`)**: It compresses the dynamic range, revealing infrastructure corridors, road networks, and smaller towns.

### 2. High-Contrast Dark Color Palette
The colors transition smoothly from empty space to fiery energy:
*   `#06060c` (Base Space/Ocean)
*   `#140e2d` (Faint Violet Halo for low lights)
*   `#391b6f` (Deep Purple for rural settlements)
*   `#a84200` (Copper Orange for peri-urban areas)
*   `#d87e00` (Warm Amber for town centers)
*   `#f1c40f` (Golden Yellow for city cores)
*   `#ffffff` (Electric White for maximum intensity)

### 3. Anchoring the Landmass
Plotting the country boundary with a very dark fill (`#0d0d18`) behind the transparent parts of the raster anchors the map. This makes the shape of Ghana visible even in areas without any nighttime lights.

---

## 💻 Implementation Script (R)

Save this script as `visualize_ghana_nightlights.R` in your workspace.

```R
# ==============================================================================
# Premium VIIRS Nighttime Lights Visualization of Ghana
# ==============================================================================

library(sf)
library(terra)
library(tidyverse)
library(tidyterra)
library(geodata)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Environment & Paths setup
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# In Windows, if PROJ or GDAL libraries conflict, uncomment and modify:
# Sys.setenv(PROJ_LIB = "C:/Program Files/R/R-4.5.2/library/sf/proj")

dir.create("data", showWarnings = FALSE)
dir.create("output", showWarnings = FALSE)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Retrieve Ghana Boundaries (Vector)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
message("Downloading Ghana administrative boundary...")
# Level 0 gets the national outline; Level 1 gets regional boundaries.
ghana_vector <- gadm(country = "GHA", level = 0, path = "data", version = "latest") %>%
  st_as_sf()

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Load VIIRS Nightlights Raster
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Replace the path below with your downloaded VIIRS GeoTIFF
# e.g., downloaded from EOG or processed using `blackmarbler`
viirs_raster_path <- "data/ghana_viirs_2023.tif"

if (!file.exists(viirs_raster_path)) {
  stop(paste(
    "Please download the VIIRS GeoTIFF for Ghana and save it at:",
    viirs_raster_path,
    "\nAlternative: Access the data via Google Earth Engine or NASA Earthdata."
  ))
}

message("Loading and processing raster data...")
viirs_raw <- rast(viirs_raster_path)

# Ensure the coordinate reference systems align
ghana_projected <- st_transform(ghana_vector, crs(viirs_raw))

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. Spatial Operations: Crop & Mask
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Crop limits the extent; Mask removes pixels outside the boundary
viirs_cropped <- crop(viirs_raw, ghana_projected)
viirs_masked <- mask(viirs_cropped, vect(ghana_projected))

# Apply log1p transformation to bring out subtle rural lights and roads
viirs_log <- log1p(viirs_masked)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. Styling and Plotting
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
message("Styling cartographic elements...")

# Premium night-glow color ramp
nightlights_palette <- c(
  "#06060c", # Dark space background (no light)
  "#140e2d", # Faint purple-blue halo (very low light)
  "#391b6f", # Deep violet (low-medium light)
  "#a84200", # Copper orange (medium light)
  "#d87e00", # Warm amber (medium-high light)
  "#f1c40f", # Golden yellow (high light)
  "#ffffff"  # Electric white (intense urban centers)
)

p <- ggplot() +
  # Layer 1: Dark grey/blue basemap to anchor the shape of Ghana
  geom_sf(
    data = ghana_projected,
    fill = "#0d0d18",
    color = "#1d1d2f",
    linewidth = 0.25
  ) +
  
  # Layer 2: VIIRS SpatRaster Layer
  geom_spatraster(data = viirs_log) +
  
  # Layer 3: Visual Scale Styling
  scale_fill_gradientn(
    colors = nightlights_palette,
    na.value = "transparent",
    name = "Luminosity Index (Log Scale)"
  ) +
  
  # Layer 4: Standardize space
  coord_sf(expand = FALSE) +
  
  # Theme Overrides
  theme_void() +
  theme(
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#06060c", color = NA),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#06060c", color = NA),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.title = element_text(color = "gray80", size = 8.5, face = "bold"),
    legend.text = element_text(color = "gray60", size = 7.5),
    legend.key.width = unit(1.8, "cm"),
    legend.key.height = unit(0.25, "cm"),
    plot.title = element_text(
      color = "#ffffff", 
      size = 18, 
      face = "bold", 
      hjust = 0.5, 
      margin = margin(t = 25, b = 5)
    ),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(
      color = "gray75", 
      size = 10, 
      hjust = 0.5, 
      margin = margin(b = 20)
    ),
    plot.caption = element_text(
      color = "gray45", 
      size = 7, 
      hjust = 0.5, 
      margin = margin(t = 15, b = 20)
    )
  ) +
  
  # Typography / Labels
  labs(
    title = "GHANA AT NIGHT",
    subtitle = "Infrastructure corridors & urban settlement patterns observed via VIIRS satellite sensors",
    caption = "Data: NASA Black Marble VIIRS DNB (2023) | Cartography: R + ggplot2 + terra"
  )

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. Save Visualization (High Resolution)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
message("Saving map to output/ghana_nightlights_map.png...")
ggsave(
  filename = "output/ghana_nightlights_map.png",
  plot = p,
  width = 8.5,
  height = 11,
  dpi = 400,
  bg = "#06060c"
)
message("Process complete!")
```

---

> [!TIP]
> **Enhancing the Glow (Optional)**
> For a more advanced visual aesthetic, you can use the `ggfx` package in R. Applying `ggfx::with_blur(geom_spatraster(...), sigma = 1)` creates a true atmospheric light glow effect beneath the sharp pixel centers.

> [!WARNING]
> **Data Range Anomalies**
> VIIRS data can sometimes contain negative values (due to background subtraction algorithms) or extreme outliers (from gas flares or lightning). Filtering out negative values using `viirs_masked[viirs_masked < 0] <- 0` before processing ensures a clean log transform.
